-- Cheung Kong Infrastructure, MTR Corp., Yanzhou: Hong Kong Equity Preview
-- Ronnie Koo
-- 2010-07-30T01:26:41Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-20/china-s-developers-byd-insurers-petrochina-hong-kong-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The  following  companies may have
significant price changes in Hong Kong trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  
 The  Hang Seng Index  gained 2.64 points, or less than 0.1
percent, to 21,093.82.  The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index ,
which tracks so-called H shares of Chinese companies, fell 0.3
percent to 11,942.21.  
 Insurance companies: China may issue rules next month that
allow insurers to increase the amount of assets they are allowed
to invest in A-shares, A-share funds, bond funds and money
market funds, the Shanghai Securities News reported today,
without citing anyone.  
 China Life Insurance Co.  (2628 HK), the nation’s biggest
insurer, retreated 0.3 percent to HK$34.70.  China Pacific
Insurance (Group) Co.  (2601 HK), the third largest, slipped 1
percent to HK$30.90.  
 Cheung Kong Infrastructure Holdings Ltd.  (1038 HK): The
company paid 5.8 billion pounds ($9.1 billion) for Electricite
de France SA’s U.K. electricity networks unit, the Financial
Times said, citing an unidentified person close to the talks.
 Wendy Tong Barnes , a spokeswoman for Cheung Kong Infrastructure
in Hong Kong, said by telephone today she was unable to comment
on the report. The unit of Hong Kong billionaire  Li Ka-shing ’s
Hutchison Whampoa ltd. slipped 0.9 percent to HK$28.90.  
 Industrial and Commercial Bank of China Ltd.  (1398 HK): The
world’s biggest lender by market value has approached Chong Hing
Bank Ltd. (1111 HK) about acquiring the Hong Kong-based lender,
Sina.com reported, citing unidentified people from the banking
industry. Shares rose 1 percent to HK$5.94. Chong Hing Bank,
controlled by Hong Kong’s Liu family, climbed 4.1 percent to
HK$15.22.  
 MTR Corp.  (66 HK): The company will discuss the future of
 Prudence Chan , chief executive officer at unit Octopus Holdings
Ltd., at a special board meeting today after she said Octopus
sold customers’ personal data, Ming Pao Daily reported, without
saying where it obtained the information. Octopus, a provider of
electronic-payment services, is 57.4 percent owned by MTR, which
operates Hong Kong’s underground trains and develops property.
Shares dropped 0.4 percent to HK$27.40.  
 Yanzhou Coal Mining Co.  (1171 HK): The Chinese miner cut
its estimate for the likely increase in first-half profit to 35
percent in a statement to Hong Kong’s stock exchange on July 29.
Yanzhou previously estimated a gain of more than 100 percent.
The company said that fluctuations in the exchange rate of the
Australian and U.S. dollars resulted in a loss on a loan. The
stock slid 1 percent to HK$16.88.  
